In the Rules index and history views the filter section
appears to have more allocated space than it needs. This change
reduces from there and adds to the pagination widget to allow
for the elasticity of the same without ugly wrapping to the next line

pulltitle: Bug 1296683 - use horizontal space better in rule create/edit dialogs
pullsbody:
Following up Friday's discussion on IRC: Tab key seems to be broken only when running `lineman run`. I ran the changes in the main balrog repo and Tab was fine there.

I noticed the dist/ folder needs to be commited each time. I wonder if it wouldn't be better to ignore the folder out of the repo and trigger the frontend build in the admin docker image.
pull_commit_message: Bug 1296683 - use horizontal space better in rule create/edit dialogs

pullsbody:
This provides some basic UI for managing Scheduled Rule Changes. The drop down from "Rules" was the best I could come up with for Nav. I thought it made sense to keep it either there or as a link in the body of the page, as it's specifically related to Rules.

The UI for the new section is just a basic CRUD ui, largely a copy of the Rules stuff with extra fields added. I spent some time fussing with a datetime picker, because I couldn't think of any other reasonable way to configure that kind of change. You'll notice that it doesn't close automatically for some reason - I haven't been able to figure out why.

I added a button on the Rules page to create a Scheduled Change based on an existing Rule - I expect that's what we'll be using the vast majority of the time.

I made a couple of fixes related to error handling as part of this as well - there were some types of errors that resulted in no message in the UI (merely the console).

Running this patch along with https://github.com/mozilla/balrog/pull/103 should give you a fully working system that lets you add scheduled changes with the agent running to process them.
pull_commit_message: Remove unused file.

I made a couple of fixes related to error handling as part of this as well - there were some types of errors that resulted in no message in the UI (merely the console).

Running this patch along with https://github.com/mozilla/balrog/pull/103 should give you a fully working system that lets you add scheduled changes with the agent running to process them.
pull_commit_message: Add WIP datetime picker.

pullsbody:
There has been no objections to this, only the casual comment that if I could make fail/pass different we'd be better off (I can't at this time).

This does the following:
-    All "header" entries (start of line) are bolded
-    The Build Number is de-emphasized (currently in chatzilla it links to a channel, here I color it grey)
-    The success/failure message is colored (though due to a travis limitation, is not colored red/green, so to avoid confusion on glancing I chose blue, so it stands out but doesn't evoke pass-fail mentality)
-    All urls are grey to try and avoid them disrupting skim-flow of IRC conversation
-    Checkin Comment is also grey.

pulltitle: Bug 1076810 - RelEng CI tests should be available over the internet, add irc notifications for balrog-ui repository,r=mgerva
pullsbody:
Hey Massimo,
A review request for you! Basically, I spotted this repo was failing in travis from looking at http://egeloen.fr/travis-wall/#/petemoore and then I noticed there are no irc notifications, so this might be why nobody noticed. Therefore I added irc notifications to it. We got this from the last build:

travis-ci [travis-ci@moz-0eh38k.compute-1.amazonaws.com] entered the room.
travis-ci
12:27:48 petemoore/balrog-ui#1 (bug1076810 - 88bbb95 : Pete Moore): The build failed.
12:27:48 Change view : https://github.com/petemoore/balrog-ui/commit/88bbb95798fa
12:27:48 Build details : http://travis-ci.org/petemoore/balrog-ui/builds/46059207
12:27:48 Commit message : Bug 1076810 - RelEng CI tests should be available over the internet, add irc notifications for balrog-ui repository,r=mgerva
12:27:48 travis-ci left the room.

I already put the r=mgerva in the commit message, so that if you accept the merge request, the comment will reflect it. This commit only lives in my own personal fork at the moment.

Thanks,
Pete
